General Guideline for Maintain AWS CodeCommit
Repository
This tutorial will help you to learn most of the functions and capabilities in the AWS CodeCommit and
this tutorial does not based on Git commands. Therefore, no prior Git knowledge need to follow this
series.
In this tutotial, you can follow,

Step 1 : Create a CodeCommit repository
If you do not have a CodeCommit repository yet, please follow the bellow steps to create a repository.
1) Open the CodeCommit console using
https://console.aws.amazon.com/codesuite/codecommit/home.
2) If you need to change your region use regional selector at the top right conner. Otherwise do
not change or do anything and it will automatically select the correct region related to you.
3) Choose Create repository at the top right conner.
4) On the Create repository page, you have to fill bellow details.
(i) Repository name: Enter a suitable name for your repository (for example my-demo-
repo). We highly recommend you to follow a standard way for this naming convention.
(ii) Description (optional): Enter a short description about your project (for example
demostration repository)
(iii) Tags (optional): Add one or more tags (this will help your organization or the compnay
to manage your AWS services)
(iv) Enable Amazon CodeGuru Reviewer for Java and Python (optional): If you enable this
option, CodeGuru will analyze your Java or Python code(if you have). It will
automatically suggests imporvements.
(v) Choose create option
Step 2: Add files to your repository
After doing the above step 1, you can now see the below interface.
 You can add your local file into this repository or you can create a new file by clicking a Create
file option. If you create/upload the first file to the repo, a branch will automatically generated
and it’s name called ‘main’.
 Using git client to clone the CodeCommit repository to your local computer, and then you can
easily do commiting, pushing and merging your files.
Usually we go with the upload file option to upload a local computer file to the repository and you
should follow the below steps.
1. Choose Add file, and then choose upload a file option to upload a file in your local
computer.
2. After that upload file window, you have to fill the below details.
(i) Author name : Enter the name you want displayed to other repository users.
(ii) Email address: Enter your/organization email address.
(iii) Commit message (optional) : Enter a brief message and we higly recommend that
you add a commit message to help your teammates to understand why you added
this file.
(iv) Select Commit changes.
Step 3 : How to maintain the repository using AWS Sagemaker
Please follow my Github repository
https://github.com/Data-Fenix/maintain-codecommit-using-aws-sagemaker
Step 4 : Browse the contents of your repository
1. From repositories, click my-demo-repo.
2. The page shows the folders and files in the default branch of my-demo-repo. To change the
branch, click the arrow down button in the main option (Next to Notify button)
3. To browse the commit history of the repository, choose Commits(in the right hand side). The
console displays the commit history for the default branch(main). If you need to change the
branch once again click on the arrow down in the main button.
4. Let’s say you need to see more details about the commit, you have to click on the Commit ID
(relavent). After that you can see the more details about that commit and specially differences.
5. In Commits, choose the Commit visualizer tab.
6. In Commits, click Compare commits. In here you can compare two branches easily.( you can
compare the difference between the previous version of the file with the latest version)
Step 5: Create and collaborate on a pull request (merge request)
Let’s say you newly join to the current ongoing project and your supervisor said you do not have to start
from the begging and continue this workload. So you are new to this project and you do not need to
mess up this exiting improvement. Therefore you can copy all the files into new baranch and using that
new branch you can upgrade this project. So now you have a backup file as well. This method called pull
request.
Please follow the bellow steps to create a pull request.
1) In the navigation pane(Right hand side), choose Pull requests.
2) In Pull request, choose Create pull request.
3) Enter the Destination branch and the Source branch according to your requirement.
Source: Branch that contains the changes you want reviewed
Destination: Branch where you want the reviewed code to be merged when the pull request
is closed.
4) Choose Compare. (Ideaily it has to pop up Mergeable message)
5) Review and compare the merge details and enter a suitable Title and Description (Optional)
in the given space.
6) Press Create Pull Request button.
7) Your pull request appears in the list of pull requests for the repository and if there’s no
approval rules, you can choose the merge option in the top right conner. If you need to add
an approval rule, please follow the next section (Step 6)
8) After that it will appear the below window and choose a suitable merge strategy. If you
want to delete the source branch after the merge, tick the bottom left square box.
More details about merge strategies:
https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/merge-strategies-in-git/
9) Finally press the Merge pull request button in the bottom right conner.
Step 6: Create an approval rule
If you need to apply some approval stage before merging, you shuold create an approval rule for that.
Let’s say you are a member of team and you need to merge two branches. But your team leader need
some governance(he need some tracking system) or he need to see the changes before merge branches.
So in this case, better option is to create an approval rule in CodeCommit.
If you need to create an approval rule, follow the bellow process.
1) In the navigation pane(Right hand side), choose Approval rule template.
2) Click the Create template button and after that you can see the bellow interface.
Please follow the order in the above image and you can fill the gaps in the above image using the
following description.
1) Choose an appropriate name for your approval rule.
2) If you need you can add some short description about the rule.
3) Enter the number approval need for the conformation.
4) Press Add button to enter the responsbile persons. It’s better to use IAM user and it means you
have to enter their IAM user name.
5) Add the relevant parties’ IAM user names.You can find the IAM user by refering this image.
6) If you need to remove some members, please click the remove button.
7) If you nedd to add this approval template only for some specific branches, please add the
necessary branches using add.
8) Specify the branch name in the given space.
9) If you need to remove some branches, please click the remove button.
10) Specify the relavant code repository by clicking the drop down button.
11) Finally, review all the details in the space and if you are happy with the filled details, please click
the create button to create the approval request.
Step 7: Monitoring
Please follow my Github repository
https://github.com/Data-Fenix/aws-codecommit-alerting-system
Step 8: Manage Branches
Let’s say you need to create,view,delete or view last commits of the branch, this process will help you.
In the navigation pane(Right hand side), choose Branches.
By looking at the above image and it has highlighted few buttons.
Delete Branch : Delete the selected baranch form your repository.
View Branch: Select the selected baranch form your repository
View last commit: To see the commit history of the selected baranch
View last commit: Another option to create a pull request.
Create branch: To create a new branch and after clicking this option it will appear bellow window.
You can create a new branch after enter a suitable barnch name and reference branch in the empty
boxes.
Step 9: Clean Up
If you need to delete this repository, follow the bellow steps:
1) Open the CodeCommit console
using https://console.aws.amazon.com/codesuite/codecommit/home.
2) In Repositories, choose the relavant repository and in this case my-demo-repo.
3) In the navigation pane, choose Settings.
4) In the Settings page, in Delete repository, choose Delete repository.
5) Type delete, and then choose Delete. This will permanently delete your repository from the
CodeCommit.
Now you are faimiliarize with the CodeCommit and you can start store your files, codes and other
documents in the CodeCommit.
